Anonymous Tue 23 Mar 2021 01:43:28 No.37313731 Report

>>37313066
Difficult to tell, everyone's brain is wired differently. What helps others, holds others back. I have a few things, which are of an intermediate-ish level.

Life refs are a good thing and virtually all artists do them.
Directly targeting the "fundamentals" is very important, you can go to /ic/ and read the sticky for some pointers. Don't bother with the rest of the board, they are miserable assholes.

When it comes to a specific exercise, the one described in the following video is described as being anywhere between 'kinda insightful' and 'completely life-changing':
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MJYGFwGhHnA

That is from Proko's channel. I would recommend to watch many of his guest videos. Seeing other artists at work and listening to them explaining can often help you kick off something of your own.

And as a bonus: The three most important things I personally have ever learned about drawing:

1) Teach yourself the ability to visualize what your drawing is gonna be and be able to think ahead as you are putting it on paper. You know what your drawing is gonna be, you only have to render it (unfortunately very difficult to learn if you aren't blessed with the ability from birth, but a fundamentally important ability)

2) Avoid tunnel vision. Learn to love your peripheral vision. What happens to some artists is that they get carried away by a small part of their drawing that chokes the entire rest of the drawing. Keep track of what goes where and how it is proportioned against each other

3) Keep your distance from your paper to make sure your field of view is as broad as possible. Use your entire arm to draw if the size of pen stroke requires it.

You may already be aware of these, but I like to mention them since they are often seen as a given when not everyone does these.

If I could add some tips that have helped me:

Be very deliberate with your placement of anything, especially lines
If you're working with digital then flip your canvas often.
Look at your work from a distance to check overall composition. My goal is to make something that's immediately readable at any distance, even from the thumbnail it should be clear what the piece is
Also look at how other artists tackle the problems you're facing, liferefs are good but so is successful attempts at rendering them. A good artist steals
